narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learned a lot about how things move and interact, physics-wise. Fun!
This course gave a great crash course on solving particle collision, rigid bodies, and vibrations.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: This course was taught very well, considering this was her first time teaching this class. There were ample resources, and a lot of good time in class to learn all about dynamics. I thought that the second midterm was substantially harder than the first midterm and the final, so perhaps this could be evened out.

This course was pretty interesting for a pset-focused/ purely problem-solving based class. Dr. Prabhakar was super engaging and made the content fun to learn. The psets were nicely spaced out, as were the exams, making the pace of the course very manageable. The 24 hour extensions and points back for test corrections also made it much easier to properly learn the content, as you didn't have to worry as much about cramming/rushing assignments, and also made me really go back and learn topics I had missed on exams.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes, especially with Dr. Prabhakar! She is a fantastic professor  really thorough with her explanations and ensuring that everyone understands the content completely during lecture. Dynamics was a great class to expand upon previous concepts learned in Statics and Physics and helped me understand how to analyze moving systems a bit better. You learn a lot about particle/rigid body kinematics and kinetics, although the learning in 3D is a bit limited. Exams and psets are very reasonable.
Yes! Especially with Prabhakar. The content you learn is actually very interesting and applicable in the real world.
Yes, if you're an engineering major and like problem solving / pset based classes. Take it with Dr. Prabhakar, she's fantastic!
